{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a9bc72d6-02db-460f-8021-e59e5d607e4a","content":"**Exit code 8** is MTP's \"zero tests discovered\" code. VSTest returned 0 in that scenario; MTP intentionally treats it as a failure. Since your `ConditionalTests.cs` compiles away all tests when `INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS` is not defined, MTP exits with 8.\n\n**Two ways to fix it:**\n\n### Option 1 — CI pipeline command (recommended)\nAdd `--ignore-exit-code 8` after `--` in your `dotnet test` call:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --ignore-exit-code 8\n```\n\n### Option 2 — Environment variable\nSet this in your CI environment so it applies globally:\n\n```bash\nexport TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE=8\ndotnet test\n```\n\nBoth tell MTP to map exit code 8 → 0. Real test failures (exit code 2) are still reported as failures.\n\nLet me verify this works with your project:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01SBb3LFb3BUsSF1LAfuoG8y","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-9458528583654145a6ee7a62a725082e && dotnet test 2>&1; echo \"EXIT CODE: $?\"","description":"Run dotnet test without fix to confirm exit code 8","initial_wait":30},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run dotnet test without fix to confirm exit code 8"}],"interactionId":"09f79e2b-053e-4c33-8534-c1734721251d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The issue is clear. With MTP, when no tests are discovered (because `INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS` is not defined, so all tests are compiled out), the runner returns exit code 8 (which means \"no tests found\"). VSTest returned 0 in this case.\n\nThe fix is to set the `--ignore-exit-code` option or use the environment variable `TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE` to tell MTP to return 0 when no tests are found. Alternatively, you can set `<TestingPlatformExitCodeOnNoTests>0</TestingPlatformExitCodeOnNoTests>` in the project file... let me think about the exact mechanism.\n\n\nActually, the best approach is to use `dotnet test -- --ignore-exit-code 8` to tell MTP to treat the \"no tests discovered\" exit code as success, or set the environment variable `TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE=8` to achieve the same effect. I'm settling on the two most practical approaches: either passing the flag directly to the `dotnet test` command in the CI pipeline, or setting the environment variable before running tests. There's no built-in MSBuild property that would handle this at the project level.","outputTokens":962,"requestId":"CFC0:1F3FEB:E826C2B:10143215:69EC0F4B"},"id":"c0f00fb6-d153-497c-8c0c-9f4cde661411","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:48:30.252Z","parentId":"d3e6080b-ba69-448f-8c06-ed7514a43d89"}
